{{Short description|Tectonic block near the Yucatan Peninsula}} {{use dmy dates|date=June 2022}} {{use British English|date=June 2022}}<!-- strong national ties to Belize --> {{Infobox landform <!-- used in absence of an infobox for continental fragments or microcontinents ie sub-divisions of tectonic plates --> | water = | name = Maya Block | other_name = {{hlist|Maya Terrane|Yucatan Block|Yucatan{{nbnd}}Chiapas Block}} | photo = Maya Block USGS OF-97-470-L 1-2.tif | photo_width = | photo_alt = | photo_caption = Maya Block {{small|/ detail of 2006 map by French & Schenk / via USGS}} | map = North America | map_width = | map_caption = | map_alt = | relief = 1 | label = Maya Block | label_position = top | mark = | marker_size = | location = [[Belize]], northern [[Guatemala]], southeastern [[Mexico]] | grid_ref = | grid_ref_UK = | grid_ref_Ireland = | coordinates = {{coord|20.445647077397183|-89.58898720418905|type:country_region:XA_dim:1500km|display=inline,title}}<!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | coordinates_ref = | range = | part_of = [[North American Plate]] | water_bodies = | elevation_ft = <!-- or |elevation_m = --> | elevation_ref = | surface_elevation_ft = <!-- or |surface_elevation_m = --> | surface_elevation_ref = | highest_point = | highest_elevation = | highest_coords = | length = {{convert|760|mi|km|abbr=on}} | width = {{convert|450|mi|km|abbr=on}} | area = {{convert|233130|mi2|km2|abbr=on}}<!-- {{Convert|NN|ha|acres}} --> | depth = | drop = | formed_by = | geology = [[Tectonic block|tectonic or crustal block]] | age = | orogeny = | volcanic_arc/belt = | volcanic_arc = | volcanic_belt = | volcanic_field = | eruption = | last_eruption = | topo = | operator = | designation = | free_label_1 = | free_data_1 = | free_label_2 = | free_data_2 = | free_label_3 = | free_data_3 = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | embedded = }} The '''Maya Block''', also known as the '''Maya Terrane''', '''Yucatan Block''', or '''Yucatan{{nbnd}}Chiapas Block''', is a [[Physiographic regions of the world|physiographic or geomorphic region]] and [[Tectonic block|tectonic or crustal block]] in the southernmost portion of the [[North American Plate]].
== Extent == The terrestrial limits of the Block are commonly given as the Vista Hermosa and [[Motagua Fault|Motagua Fault Systems]] (ie East Mexican Transform and Motagua{{nbnd}}Polochic Fault Zone), with submarine limits commonly given as the edges of the [[Campeche Bank]].{{sfn|Bundschuh|Alvarado|2012|p=3|loc=fig. 1.1}}{{sfn|Dengo|1969|p=312}}{{sfn|Ross|Stockli|Rasmussen|Gulick|2021|p=243|loc=fig. 1}} The first fault divides the Block from the Oaxaquia Block (ie Juarez, Cuicateco, or Oaxaquia Block, Terrane, or microcontinent), while the latter fault divides it from the [[Chortis Block]].{{sfn|Martens|2009|pp=6-9}}{{sfn|Ross|Stockli|Rasmussen|Gulick|2021|p=243|loc=fig. 1}}{{notetag|The Maya Block was first defined as 'the area [of Central America ie of that land and continental shelf which extends from the Isthmus of Tehuantepec in Mexico to the Atrato lowland in Colombia] north of the Motagua fault zone [...] [ie] northern Guatemala, Belice [Belize], the states of Chiapas, Tabasco, Campeche, Yucatán and Quintana Roo in Mexico, and the Campeche Bank in the Gulf of Mexico' {{harv|Dengo|1969|p=312}}.}}
It has been recently suggested that the Block's terrestrial limits extend further along the Gulf of Mexico, past the Vista Hermosa Fault, into Louisiana.{{sfn|Zhao|Xiao|Gulick|Morgan|2020|p=129|loc=fig. 1}}{{sfn|Ortega-Gutierrez|Elias-Herrera|Moran-Zenteno|Solari|2018|p=3|loc=fig. 1}}
== Geography == === Political === The terrestrial portion of the Block encompasses all six [[districts of Belize]], five northerly [[departments of Guatemala]] (ie Huehuetenango, Quiche, Alta Verapaz, Izabal, Peten), and five southeasterly [[List of states of Mexico|states of Mexico]] (ie Chiapas, Tabasco, Campeche, Yucatan, and Quintana Roo). Its submarine portion encompasses the continental shelf which abuts the coastal districts.
=== Basement === The Block sits on a crystalline, igneous-metamorphic basement, which is exposed in at least five formations, ie the Mixtequita Massif, Chiapas Massif, Cuchumatanes Dome, Tucuru{{nbnd}}Teleman, and the [[Maya Mountains]].{{sfn|Martens|2009|p=18}}
=== Provinces === [[File:Maya Block USGS OF-97-470-L 1-2.tif|thumb|upright=1.7|Maya Block {{small|/ detail of 2006 map by French & Schenk / via USGS}}]] The Block fully encompasses four geologic provinces (ie [[Yucatan Platform]], [[Maya Mountains]], Macuspana Basin, and Villahermosa Uplift), and partially encompasses a further six (ie Sierra Madre de Chiapas{{nbnd}}Peten Foldbelt, Chiapas Massif{{nbnd}}Nuclear Central America, Pacific Offshore Basin, Saline{{nbnd}}Comalcalco Basin, Campeche{{nbnd}}Sigsbee Salt Basin, and Greater Antilles Deformed Belt).{{sfn|French|Schenk|2004}}{{sfn|French|Schenk|2006}}
=== Basins === The block fully encompasses three sedimentary basins (ie Campeche, Yucatan, and Peten{{nbnd}}Corozal), and partially encompasses a further one (ie Sureste).{{sfn|Evenick|2021|p=6|loc=fig. 4}}
=== Faults === The Block encompasses a number of faults.{{citation needed|date=June 2022}} It is further delimited by two faults (ie Vista Hermosa and Motagua).{{sfn|Martens|2009|p=9}}
==== Motagua ==== {{main|Motagua Fault}} The [[Motagua Fault|Motagua Fault System]] is composed of six subparallel [[Fault (geology)|faults]], all of which contribute to the sinistral [[Cenozoic]] slip between the [[Caribbean Plate|Caribbean]] and [[North American Plate|North American plates]].{{sfn|Martens|2009|p=9}} Its constituent faults are the [[Chixoy-Polochic Fault|Polochic or Chixoy{{nbnd}}Polochic]], Panima, Baja Verapaz, San Agustin, Cabañas or Cabañas{{nbnd}}Jubuco or Motagua, and Jocotan{{nbnd}}Chamelecon.{{sfn|Martens|2009|pp=9-11}}{{notetag|There is no widespread agreement regarding which constituent fault of the Motagua Fault System divides the Maya and Chortis Blocks {{harv|Martens|2009|p=12}}.}}
== Geology == === Formation === The Block is thought to have formed before or during the opening of the [[Iapetus Ocean]].{{sfn|Ross|Stockli|Rasmussen|Gulick|2021|p=243}} It, together with the Oaxaquia, Suwannee, and Carolina blocks, constituted a peri-Gondwanan terrane on that continent's western, northwestern, or eastern edge during the Appalachian{{nbnd}}Caledonian or Ouachita{{nbnd}}Marathon{{nbnd}}Appalachian orogeny (ie during the formation of [[Pangaea]] from the collision of [[Gondwana]] and [[Laurentia]]).{{sfn|Zhao|Xiao|Gulick|Morgan|2020|p=129}}{{sfn|Guzman-Hidalgo|Grajales-Nishimura|Eberli|Aguayo-Camargo|2021|p=15}}{{sfn|Ross|Stockli|Rasmussen|Gulick|2021|pp=242-243}} It is thought to have been displaced away from the Laurentian craton by clockwise rotation, translation, or anticlockwise rotation, during the [[Middle Jurassic]] opening of the [[Gulf of Mexico]].{{sfn|Guzman-Hidalgo|Grajales-Nishimura|Eberli|Aguayo-Camargo|2021|p=15}}{{sfn|Ross|Stockli|Rasmussen|Gulick|2021|p=254}}{{notetag|The palaeogeographic positions and tectonic interactions of pre-[[Mesozoic]] crustal blocks in present-day [[Mexico]], [[Central America]], and the [[Caribbean]] are still debated {{harv|Ross|Stockli|Rasmussen|Gulick|2021|p=242}}. Fixing the pre-Mesozoic position of the Maya Black with respect to the southwestern margin of [[Laurentia]] is an important step in plate reconstructions of the assembly of [[Pangaea]] and the rotation-induced rifting and opening of the [[Gulf of Mexico]] {{harv|Ross|Stockli|Rasmussen|Gulick|2021|p=242}}.}}
=== Movement === The Block is thought to experience significant counterclockwise rotation and a north-northwest down tilt, which gradually lowers the northern portion of the [[Yucatan Peninsula]], thereby lifting its southern extreme in the [[Maya Mountains]].{{sfn|Monroy-Rios|2020|pp=34-35, 90}} It is nonetheless tectonically rigid or stable.{{sfn|Monroy-Rios|2020|pp=34-35}}
== Scholarship == The Block was discovered in 1969 by Gabriel Dengo, a Guatemalan geographer.{{sfn|Dengo|1969|p=312}}{{sfn|Martens|2009|p=6}} It was quickly adopted in scholarship, and remains 'accepted by many as a valid subdivision of Central America's geology, especially of its crystalline basement.'{{sfn|Martens|2009|p=6}}
